<DocsLayout title="Decision Lifecycle" description="How decisions age, go stale, and get refreshed.">
  <h1>Decision Lifecycle</h1>

  <p>
    Decisions are not permanent. The world changes — requirements shift, load increases, team grows,
    dependencies update. quint-code treats every decision as having a shelf life.
  </p>

  <h2>The lifecycle</h2>

  <pre><code>Pending Implementation → Shipped → Active → Stale → Superseded/Deprecated

Pending:     Decision recorded, not yet implemented (no measurement)
Shipped:     Implemented and measured (verdict: accepted/partial/failed)
Active:      Shipped, R_eff ≥ 0.5, not expired
Stale:       R_eff &lt; 0.5, or valid_until expired, or code drift detected
Superseded:  Replaced by a newer decision
Deprecated:  No longer relevant (archived)</code></pre>

  <h2>Evidence and R_eff</h2>

  <p>
    Every decision can have evidence attached — test results, benchmarks, user feedback, measurements.
    Each evidence item has:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Verdict</strong> — supports, weakens, or refutes the decision</li>
    <li><strong>Congruence Level (CL)</strong> — how relevant is this evidence to this context?
      <ul>
        <li>CL3: Same project, same context — full weight</li>
        <li>CL2: Similar project, similar stack — 0.1 penalty</li>
        <li>CL1: Different context — 0.4 penalty</li>
        <li>CL0: Opposed context — 0.9 penalty</li>
      </ul>
    </li>
    <li><strong>Expiry date</strong> — when this evidence is no longer trustworthy</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    <strong>R_eff</strong> (effective reliability) is computed as the minimum across all evidence
    scores, with CL penalties applied. This is the weakest link principle: the chain is as strong
    as its weakest link.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>R_eff ≥ 0.5 — healthy, decision is trustworthy</li>
    <li>R_eff &lt; 0.5 — degraded, needs review</li>
    <li>R_eff &lt; 0.3 — AT RISK, needs immediate attention</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Code drift detection</h2>

  <p>
    After a decision is implemented, the agent snapshots affected file hashes. quint-code then
    snapshots the file hashes. On every <code>/q-refresh scan</code>, it recomputes hashes and
    detects changes:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>MODIFIED</strong> — file changed since baseline (may or may not invalidate the decision)</li>
    <li><strong>FILE MISSING</strong> — file was deleted or moved (likely needs decision update)</li>
    <li><strong>No drift</strong> — file unchanged</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Drift is a signal, not an automatic invalidation. The agent reads the diff and judges whether
    the change is material (broke an invariant) or cosmetic (comments, formatting).
  </p>

  <h2>Module coverage</h2>

  <p>
    <code>/q-status</code> shows module coverage — which parts of your codebase are governed by
    decisions and which are blind spots:
  </p>

  <pre><code>## Module Coverage (9 modules, 77% governed)
  ✓ src/internal/artifact — 3 decisions
  ✓ src/internal/codebase — 2 decisions
  ✗ src/assurance          — no decisions (blind)
  ✗ src/cmd/indexer        — no decisions (blind)</code></pre>

  <p>
    Blind modules are parts of your architecture with no formal engineering decisions. Not necessarily
    bad — but worth knowing about.
  </p>

  <h2>Refreshing decisions</h2>

  <pre><code>/q-refresh</code></pre>

  <p>Actions:</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Action</th>
        <th>What it does</th>
        <th>When to use</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><code>scan</code></td>
        <td>Find all stale artifacts + code drift</td>
        <td>Routine health check</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>waive</code></td>
        <td>Extend validity with justification</td>
        <td>Decision still valid, just expired</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>reopen</code></td>
        <td>Start new problem cycle from old decision</td>
        <td>Conditions changed, need to reconsider</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>supersede</code></td>
        <td>Replace with a different artifact</td>
        <td>New decision replaces old one</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>deprecate</code></td>
        <td>Archive as no longer relevant</td>
        <td>Decision obsolete, nothing replaces it</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>reconcile</code></td>
        <td>Find notes that overlap with decisions</td>
        <td>Clean up duplicate knowledge</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>The lemniscate</h2>

  <p>
    The full cycle is an infinity loop — the <strong>lemniscate</strong> from
    <a href="https://github.com/ailev/FPF" target="_blank" rel="noopener">FPF</a>.
    It has two halves:
  </p>

  <pre><code>Left cycle (observe):          Right cycle (act):
  Signals, drift, evidence  →    Frame → Char → Explore →
  ← Measure, learn, reframe      Compare → Decide → Implement</code></pre>

  <p>
    quint-code implements concrete mechanisms at each stage to make this loop
    close automatically instead of depending on human memory:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Observe</strong> — drift detection watches for code changes under decisions.
      <code>/q-refresh scan</code> finds expired evidence and R_eff degradation. Module coverage
      shows blind spots. These signals feed the left cycle without you asking.</li>
    <li><strong>Frame</strong> — <code>/q-frame</code> forces a diagnostic conversation before jumping
      to solutions. Cross-project recall surfaces related decisions from other projects.</li>
    <li><strong>Characterize</strong> — <code>/q-char</code> locks comparison criteria before options
      are visible, preventing bias.</li>
    <li><strong>Explore</strong> — <code>/q-explore</code> generates variants with mandatory weakest
      link labels. Diversity check warns if variants are too similar.</li>
    <li><strong>Compare</strong> — <code>/q-compare</code> enforces parity and identifies the Pareto front.</li>
    <li><strong>Decide</strong> — <code>/q-decide</code> records the contract. The adversarial
      verification gate challenges the decision before recording.</li>
    <li><strong>Implement</strong> — the agent baselines affected files after committing code.</li>
    <li><strong>Measure</strong> — <code>measure</code> records whether acceptance criteria were met.
      The inductive gate warns if there's no baseline (unverified implementation). CL scoring
      reflects verification quality.</li>
    <li><strong>Close the loop</strong> — failed measurements with <code>verdict: failed</code> suggest
      reopening the problem. Stale decisions surface in <code>/q-status</code>. Evidence supersession
      ensures R_eff reflects current state, not historical worst-case.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The goal is that you don't need to remember to check — the system surfaces what needs attention.
    This isn't fully automatic today (some steps require the agent to be proactive), but every
    release adds more closing mechanisms.
  </p>

